      "content": "The idea that judges are inserting their personal values into the law is a common criticism of substantive due process. Critics argue that the doctrine is too vague and open-ended, allowing judges to impose their own moral and ideological agendas on the Constitution. This perspective suggests that substantive due process is more of a tool for judges to shape the law according to their own views, rather than a strict interpretation of the text. This criticism is rooted in the fact that the Court has used substantive due process to strike down laws that reflect conservative or liberal values, often with little regard for the text of the Constitution.",
